U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement,c[2023?]  a1 online resource (1 video file (7 min., 37 sec.)) :bsound, color  atwo-dimensional moving imagebtdi2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  avideo file2rdaft  aInternet videos2lcgft  aThis is a publication issued by the United States federal government or produced with federal funds.  aIn scope of the U.S. Government Publishing Office Cataloging and Indexing Program (C&I) and Federal Depository Library Program (FDLP).  aThis informative video describes the conditions that gave rise to legislation authorizing the collection of import taxes and customs fees first envisioned by founding father Alexander Hamilton, the nation's first secretary of the Treasury. It traces the remarkable development of the country throughout the 19th and 20th centuries, including the essential role of immigration and the evolving laws and regulations that governed it through a period of rapid growth and expansion. In March 2003, the Homeland Security Act set into motion what would be the single-largest government reorganization since the creation of the Department of Defense. One of the agencies in the new Department of Homeland Security was the Bureau of Immigration and Customs Enforcement, now known as U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement, or ICE.1 aEnglish subtitles for the deaf and hard-of-hearing.  aDescription based on online resource; title from landing page (ICE viewed Apr. 20, 2026).20aU.S. Immigration and Customs EnforcementxHistory. 0aCustoms administrationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aImmigration enforcementzUnited StatesxHistory. 7aNonfiction films.2lcgft403Streaming videouhttps://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo255138704 zAddress at time of PURL creationuhttps://www.ice.gov/history  aC0bGPO  abc72 20260421b20260421  aBIBCONEWb20260421  aUNREPORTEDPUBSASKGPObyyyymmdd01747nam a22003733a 00147145820260421163815.0m     o  d f      cr ||||||||||